posts.name: Amit sucher
posts.cooked:
Today we bought for the first time TPU filament (95A), and we want to use it to make star wheels. We have seen some teams use TPU for their wheels like 5951 in their end effector, but have not seen any team use it for star wheels, so we would like to know if anyone did it and if it actually worked the same way a star wheel would. posts.name: Billfred Leverette (he/him/not Bill)
posts.cooked:
We printed round wheels instead of star ones, but there’s no reason you can’t.

IMG_1278 1920×1440 381 KB

IMG_1278 1920×1440 381 KB

IMG_1278 1920×1440 381 KB

Things I’d say:

Expect to play with slicer settings.  Wall count will drastically change how it behaves, as will flow rates.  Changing your filament supplier can also change things.  In my experience, getting a TPU print the way you want it is equal parts art and science in a way that you don’t see with PLA/PETG/other-rigid-filament prints.

I’d consider printing a rigid hub with more of a spline, so you have a more reliable way to transmit torque from the hex shaft.  Alternatively, plan to play with the size of the hex and wall count right in there to get a good fit.

posts.name: David Kravets
posts.cooked:
You absolutely can, however our team found that printing the AM or WCP star wheels with 95 TPU was way too stiff for something like coral intaking or indexing this year. We ended up buying 30/40/60a star wheels from AM instead for our prototyping and final products (which unfortunately ended up costing nearly $1000 in consumable parts…)

There’s a posibility you could modify the CAD to have thinner spokes or something similar to try to ‘soften’ the star spokes by adding flexibility while still using the harder durometer filament

We did for our ground intake this year. Although they are not very good at gripping onto things, they are very good at surviving getting hit by coral, and they worked well for us as a system to push the coral more toward the middle of our intake. We haven’t had an excuse to print star wheels, but we’ve printed a lot of intake wheels out of TPU.

One simple way to increase the grip of TPU wheels is to change the “Fuzzy Skin” setting in your slicer software. This adds random permutations to the surface of the print, which makes TPU a lot more grippy.

FuzzySkin 830×1322 109 KB FuzzySkin2 726×188 23.8 KB

FuzzySkin 830×1322 109 KB

FuzzySkin 830×1322 109 KB

FuzzySkin2 726×188 23.8 KB

FuzzySkin2 726×188 23.8 KB

We also experiment a lot with different infill patterns, wall thicknesses, and sometimes print without top/bottom layers to increase compliance.

posts.name: Nelson Green (1108 Mentor Coach Electrical Programming)
posts.cooked:
We printed some in 2022.  They held up all season for feeding in the tennis balls.

We modified the spokes to give more flexibility.  As noted the grip will be less than regular star wheels.

Some video of them flexing: https://photos.app.goo.gl/G3XnmhbtJ7zqXtGo6
